<subSubSection id="C36BB4F4FFACAB0CFD2D8BFCFCA4FBA2" pageId="14" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BCEE77FFFACAB0CFD2D8BFCFCA4FBA2" blockId="14.[685,1173,858,1729]" pageId="14">
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFACAB0CFD2D8BFCFCDFFC12" bold="true" box="[709,814,991,1012]" pageId="14">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is distinguishable from superficially similar 
<taxonomicName id="4C719CFCFFACAB0CFC798BDAFBF4FBE8" authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2014" box="[913,1029,1017,1039]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pujoliclerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wappesi">
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFACAB0CFC798BDAFC6FFBE8" box="[913,926,1017,1038]" italics="true" pageId="14">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFACAB0CFC588BDAFBF4FBE8" box="[944,1029,1017,1038]" italics="true" pageId="14">wappesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the more narrow shape of the antennal capitulum (compare 
<figureCitation id="134AFBFAFFACAB0CFD458C0CFCB8FBA2" box="[685,841,1071,1092]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="8.[175,216,1487,1506]" captionTargetBox="[167,1170,207,1464]" captionTargetId="figure-1@8.[151,1172,183,1487]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs. 21–38. Pujoliclerus species, antennae. 21) P. helvinus; 22) P. maracayensis; 23) P. bilineatus; 24) P. calceatus; 25) P. corumba; 26) P. ovatus; 27) P. wappesi; 28) P. amplus; 29) P. flavoapicalus; 30) P. gilvus; 31) P. hermani; 32) P. alajuela; 33) P. orellana; 34) P. megacavus; 35) P. oxinus; 36) P. alboordinus; 37) P. apolegmus; 38) P. catarina." pageId="14">Figs. 27 and 34</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36BB4F4FFACAB0CFD2D8C6AFCDDF9B1" pageId="14" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BCEE77FFFACAB0CFD2D8C6AFC51FA0B" blockId="14.[685,1173,858,1729]" pageId="14">
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFACAB0CFD2D8C6AFC8CFBB8" bold="true" box="[709,893,1097,1118]" pageId="14">Description. Size</emphasis>
: Length 6.0 mm; width 2.0 mm. 
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFACAB0CFCFF8C47FC66FB9F" bold="true" box="[791,919,1124,1145]" pageId="14">Integument</emphasis>
: Head mostly reddish brown, frons black; antenna brown; pronotum tricolorous, anterior margin narrowly white, then reddish brown, then black; elytra mostly brown, yellow around periphery; forelegs mostly brown, midleg and hindleg yellow; pterothorax and abdomen brown. 
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFACAB0CFC428D20FC14FAFE" bold="true" box="[938,997,1283,1304]" pageId="14">Head</emphasis>
: Eyes as wide as frons (12:12); funicular antennomeres moderately expanded, 6 
<superScript id="7C044A37FFACAB0CFC6F8D10FC67FAA7" attach="left" box="[903,918,1331,1345]" fontSize="6" pageId="14">th</superScript>
antennomere not very large (
<figureCitation id="134AFBFAFFACAB0CFD058D70FCC9FA8E" box="[749,824,1363,1384]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="8.[175,216,1487,1506]" captionTargetBox="[167,1170,207,1464]" captionTargetId="figure-1@8.[151,1172,183,1487]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs. 21–38. Pujoliclerus species, antennae. 21) P. helvinus; 22) P. maracayensis; 23) P. bilineatus; 24) P. calceatus; 25) P. corumba; 26) P. ovatus; 27) P. wappesi; 28) P. amplus; 29) P. flavoapicalus; 30) P. gilvus; 31) P. hermani; 32) P. alajuela; 33) P. orellana; 34) P. megacavus; 35) P. oxinus; 36) P. alboordinus; 37) P. apolegmus; 38) P. catarina." pageId="14">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFACAB0CFCA48D70FC68FA8E" bold="true" box="[844,921,1363,1384]" pageId="14">Thorax</emphasis>
: Pronotum slightly elongate (35:36), lateral tubercle very prominent (
<figureCitation id="134AFBFAFFACAB0CFD5D8DABFCF7FA7B" box="[693,774,1416,1437]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="19.[197,237,1538,1557]" captionTargetBox="[190,1193,191,1524]" captionTargetId="figure-1@19.[172,1193,183,1534]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figs. 62–75. Pujoliclerus species, pronota. 62) P. oxinus; 63) P. alajuela; 64) P. megacavus; 65) P. alboordinus; 66) P. pallidus; 67) P. apolegmus; 68) P. catarina; 69) P. macilentus; 70) P. megalus; 71) P. argus; 72) P. aspigalbus; 73) P. flora; 74) P. posticalis; 75) P. ostrinus." pageId="14">Fig. 64</figureCitation>
); epipleural fold broad, abruptly narrowed in posterior 2/3; asetiferous punctures large, prominent to distal elytral 2/3. 
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFACAB0CFBCF8D9EFB7CFA34" bold="true" box="[1063,1165,1469,1490]" pageId="14">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Aedeagus not available.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCEE77FFFACAB0CFD2D8DD1FCEAF9C4" blockId="14.[685,1173,858,1729]" pageId="14">
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFACAB0CFD2D8DD1FCDBF9E1" bold="true" box="[709,810,1522,1543]" pageId="14">Variation.</emphasis>
The width of the yellow sutural line varies.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCEE77FFFACAB0CFD2D8E0BFCDDF9B1" blockId="14.[685,1173,858,1729]" pageId="14">
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFACAB0CFD2D8E0BFC9CF9DB" bold="true" box="[709,877,1576,1597]" pageId="14">Natural History.</emphasis>
Specimens were collected during April.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
