<subSubSection id="C36BB4F4FFACAB0DFD2D8EB1FE3DFF14" lastPageId="15" pageId="14" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BCEE77FFFACAB0CFD2D8EB1FB62F927" blockId="14.[685,1173,858,1729]" pageId="14">
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFACAB0CFD2D8EB1FCC9F941" bold="true" box="[709,824,1682,1703]" pageId="14">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is a compound name derived from the Greek 
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFACAB0CFC3A8E8FFBFEF927" box="[978,1039,1708,1729]" italics="true" pageId="14">megas</emphasis>
(= large) and
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCEE77FFFADAB0DFF4588E1FE3DFF14" blockId="15.[173,659,194,242]" pageId="15">
the Latin 
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFADAB0DFEFD88E1FEBCFF31" box="[277,333,194,215]" italics="true" pageId="15">cavus</emphasis>
(= hole). It refers to the large punctures on the elytral disc.
</paragraph>
